<Review>My wife and I went to Tom Ham's for our 25th anniversary. We wanted spectacular views and fantastic food, and we were well pleased. I started with the calamari (my standard) and it was delicious, not greasy though the sauce could have had more kick and zing for my taste. No biggie. My wife had the bluefin crudo, caught by the chef himself, so said the waiter. It was delicious, especially with the citrus bits. I had the diver scallops for the entree - beautifully cooked and super delicious. The melted leeks, crispy artichokes, Guajillo Grits, and Andouille Sausage all made for the perfect meal. My wife had the pan seared duck breast and it was to die for. It could have been rendered more, the skin more crispy, but omg it was delicious.

Now here's a funny thing. When we arrived we were wished happy anniversary, but apparently no one told our waiter. This wasn't a problem because he was super nice as it was and mentioning anything to him would have resulted in a free dessert like the folks behind us got, and we weren't there for a free dessert. I just am puzzled as to why the waiter wasn't told.

What's important is our overall experience, and we are still talking about the food. This was our third visit to San Diego, and first to Tom Ham's. Next time we go San Diego, we'll be going to Tom Ham's again, for sure!< /Review>< Pics>
None< /Pics>
< Resp>
None< /Resp>

< rating>
4</rating>
<text>I really like Tom Hamm's. We have our boat on Harbor Island so when I'm working down at the office aka the boat, lunches at Tom Hamm's are a must. Being a sailor, I really like that its an actual lighthouse, and the interior is decorated with old charts of the bay. You can really see what's changed over the years.

There's an impressive tap list, most all of which can be ordered in 4, 8, or 16 ounce pours.

The bartenders are also top notch. They really seem to care about what goes into the cocktails they're serving. The day shift often shows off what really goes into the later night's libations. You might even learn something.

The only spot Tom's falls down for me, especially for lunch, is a few of the dishes. The menu is a little small and a little expensive for the average daily lunch. But that's okay. The civiche is awesome, the steak frites are great, and the burgers are enormous. The burgers are probably a bit too big for me really.

One thing I will note, especially on the food, is when we had our rehearsal dinner, the food was amazing. All prefix menu options that don't show up on their regular menu as far as I'm aware. I had the swordfish which was spectacular.</text><Pictures>None<//Pictures><response>None<//response>< GmapID>

<UserId.>113568104056378423415< /UserId.><name>James Jordan<//name>< Date>
1465709950705</Date>

5<//rate>
< Review>
The dining experience  in San Diego is complex and fraught with peril from the tourist traps in the Gaslamp to the joints in the East Village that put so much effort into being edgy and hip that they forget to produce great food.  In this culinary minefield is so refreshing to find a restaurant that has been a San Diego staple for many many years managing to delight the tastebuds and excite the senses.  We started with the chef's-choice dozen oysters which were extremely fresh and delightful.  I had a glass of wine while my beautiful wife tried the Sultry Sally cocktail which she thoroughly enjoyed.  The raw menu is not extensive but if our oysters were indicative it is fresh and well selected.  Moving on to some fried oysters we were astounded by the perfect counterpoint supplied by a dish of Asian inspired pickled vegetables.  My Shrimp and Grits was flavorful with fresh shrimp and nicely prepared grits and a little Andouille sausage to make it interesting.  My wife opted for the Whole Roasted Fish, sea bass. on the night we were there, perfectly roasted, presented with roasted peppers and a wonderful olive tapenade.  One of the best fish dishes I have ever eaten.  I finished off with the key lime pie  while my wife siped her second Sultry Sally.  The pie was more than the sum of its parts with the lime meringue providing a nice variation in sweetness while the sorbet broadened the palate of  tastes, temperatures and textures.  Lastly, I would be remiss if I did not mention our server, Jordan (the name is a coincidence), she did a great job looking after us and graciously listened to our endless prattle.  ONE OF THE BEST DINING EXPERIENCES WE HAVE HAD IN A VERY LONG TIME.<//Review>

<Review>This review is for their wedding services :
I had my magical and amazing wedding at Tom ham's lighthouse.
1) This places is has the amazing view of the ocean and San Diego skyline. They put in like millions of dollar of renovations and the new place is amazing. They custom build the ceremony site with a huge metal arch which is beautiful.
2) Our wedding co-coordinator was Stephanie and she was amazing, very prompt in replying to email and helped us in every step of the wedding planning. Some one here pointed out that tom ham's been not flexible which is not true, they were extremely flexible. Hey they allowed our dogs to be part of the ceremony which surprisingly a lot of other venues blatantly denied us to have our dogs being part of our ceremony on our special day.
3) The food is amazing . Ours was a mixed Indian-american wedding. The chef actually custom made all the appetizers in Indian style. the main entree was American-italian style and was really good.
4) We booked both the rooms and the price was very decent for ocean/city view venue in san diego.

This place has been everything I dreamed off for my wedding. I ddidnt have any complain. Kudos to the wedding managements.</Review><pictures>None< /pictures><Resp>None<//Resp>< gmap_id>

<Rate>5<//Rate><text>Absolutely loved my experience here from the moment I walked in - it was a perfect  afternoon lunch with harbor views and our city skyline.  Linger at an outdoor table and watch the sailboats, kayakers, paddleboarders, and jetskis go by.  You can't beat the view.  I'm happy to have discovered this place, to now have another go-to spot to recommend to out of town guests.  I always recommended C-Level lounge for the views, and Tom Ham's is right up there.

They do have their own large parking lot with an abundant number of spaces.

They have a good selection of rotating craft beers, which can be purchased in 4oz, 8oz, or 16oz sizes.

My guest loved her Tuna Nicoise salad; I got to sample one of her hard-boiled eggs which tasted like it was marinated in red wine vinegar and cinnamon - so delicious. I ordered the fish & chips - perfectly battered crispiness. For dessert we tried the  gelato for $3.00/scoop.  The baily's gelato was refreshing.  Highly recommended lunch/brunch location.<//text>< pics>

<user_name>Christie Coats<//user_name>< date>
1410151222596<//date>
<rating>5</rating><Text>I absolutely love Tom Ham's. We went there tonight and sat in the bar area and had an amazing view of the downtown skyline. We ordered some oysters and other appetizers along with some of their speciality drinks. Their bartenders simply know how to make a drink. While they will make you anything you ask for, you can also ask them for a concoction that is all their own. Tonight we requested a mule, a Tiny Bubbles from their bar menu and asked the bartender to surprise us. He executed all three flawlessly and even wrote down the ingredients of the surprise drink for us.

For dinner we ordered several different types of oysters and shrimp. Unfortunately I am allergic to shellfish so while I didn't have any, everyone in the party said they were good. One of the food runners suggested some of his favorite oysters for the second round and the group said they were superior to the first oysters ordered. He specifically suggested the Luna which our group loved. I ordered the Peach and Burrata salad. I love buratta and will go out of my way to find places that serve it. The salad was amazing and had two huge pieces of burrata included. I will be ordering again the next time I am there. I also ordered the Shishito peppers; while they were good, there were a few that were very hot which I haven't experienced at other restaurants.

Overall, we love the view and the good drinks. The great food is just a fantastic bonus. While many of the other places closer to downtown don't have adequate parking, Tom Ham's has plenty of parking at the end of Harbor Island. We also got to see an amazing sunset over the parking lot as we were leaving. We will be back.<//Text><pictures>None<//pictures><resp>None</resp>< gmap_id>
